comment: Long but simple algebraic transformations are applied to show that ` V ` , the Wallis formula for π , can be expressed in terms of ` A ` , the Stirling's approximation formula for the factorial, up to a constant factor. This will allow (in a later theorem) to determine the right constant factor to be put into the ` A ` , in order to get the exact Stirling's formula. (Contributed by Glauco Siliprandi, 29-Jun-2017.)
